description:
What: crash_info_store() checks if (crash_info.count < UINT32_MAX) before incrementing. But crash_info is in __noinit RAM, meaning it contains arbitrary garbage on first boot (power cycle).

Why it matters: The count field could start at any value including UINT32_MAX-1 or close to it. The check prevents overflow but doesn't prevent the count from being meaningless garbage. This is not a security issue but a correctness issue - the 'lifetime tracking' mentioned in the comment won't work reliably across power cycles.

Evidence:
```c
__noinit static struct {
    uint32_t magic;
    // ...
    uint32_t count;  // uninitialized on power-up
} crash_info;

void crash_info_store(...) {
    // ...
    if (crash_info.count < UINT32_MAX) {
        crash_info.count++;  // increments garbage
    }
}
```

Note: The magic field guards against interpreting uninitialized data during check_and_clear(), but count is still incremented in crash_info_store() without first checking magic.
